[2026-01-21 02:48:04] [INFO] Full LLM response:
To prove that the Galois cohomology $H^q(\text{Gal}(L/K), \mathcal{O}_L^\times)$ is trivial for $q > 0$ in an unramified extension of non-archimedean local fields, we use the fact that the valuation exact sequence $0 \to \mathcal{O}_L^\times \to L^\times \xrightarrow{v} \mathbb{Z} \to 0$ splits as a sequence of $G$-modules (since the extension is unramified, a uniformizer of $K$ serves as a uniformizer of $L$ and is fixed by $G$). This splitting implies that $H^q(\text{Gal}(L/K), \mathcal{O}_L^\times)$ is a direct summand of $H^q(\text{Gal}(L/K), L^\times)$.

Furthermore, for an unramified extension, the map $H^q(\text{Gal}(L/K), L^\times) \to H^q(\text{Gal}(L/K), \mathbb{Z})$ induced by the valuation is an isomorphism (by Local Class Field Theory). Since the sequence splits, the kernel of this map (which corresponds to the units cohomology) must be zero.

The imported module `ClassFieldTheory.IsNonarchimedeanLocalField.ValuationExactSequence` contains the necessary results, specifically the theorem stating that the units cohomology is zero for unramified extensions in positive degrees.

```lean
open ValuativeRel
instance [IsUnramified K L] (q : ℕ) [NeZero q] :
    Subsingleton (groupCohomology (Rep.units Gal(L/K) 𝒪[L]) q) :=
  (ValuationExactSequence.units_cohomology_isZero K L q).subsingleton
```
